04497nam a22007095i 9780231513074DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979969456  a97802315130747 a10.7312/pati142222doi  a(DE-B1597)459202  a(OCoLC)787847803  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0280002bisacsh04a2102221 aPatil, Parimal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAgainst a Hindu God :bBuddhist Philosophy of Religion in India /cParimal Patil. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Comparative Philosophy of Religions -- tPart 1. Epistemology -- t2. Religious Epistemology in Classical India: In Defense of a Hindu God -- t3. Against Irvara: Ratnakirti’s Buddhist Critique -- tPart 2. Language, Mind, and Ontology -- t4. The Theory of Exclusion, Conceptual Content, and Buddhist Epistemology -- t5. Ratnakirti’s World: Toward a Buddhist Philosophy of Everything -- tConclusion -- t6. The Values of Buddhist Epistemology -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhilosophical arguments for and against the existence of God have been crucial to Euro-American and South Asian philosophers for over a millennium. Critical to the history of philosophy in India, were the centuries-long arguments between Buddhist and Hindu philosophers about the existence of a God-like being called Isvara and the religious epistemology used to support them. By focusing on the work of Ratnakirti, one of the last great Buddhist philosophers of India, and his arguments against his Hindu opponents, Parimal G. Patil illuminates South Asian intellectual practices and the nature of philosophy during the final phase of Buddhism in India.Based at the famous university of Vikramasila, Ratnakirti brought the full range of Buddhist philosophical resources to bear on his critique of his Hindu opponents' cosmological/design argument. At stake in his critique was nothing less than the nature of inferential reasoning, the metaphysics of epistemology, and the relevance of philosophy to the practice of religion. In developing a proper comparative approach to the philosophy of religion, Patil transcends the disciplinary boundaries of religious studies, philosophy, and South Asian studies and applies the remarkable work of philosophers like Ratnakirti to contemporary issues in philosophy and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGod (Hinduism). 0aKnowledge, Theory of (Buddhism). 0aNyaya. 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Buddhist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/pati1422240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231513074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231513074/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK